04541nam a22006375i 9780691187037DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181997nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911870377 a10.1515/97806911870372doi  a(DE-B1597)501697  a(OCoLC)1076414568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a801/.95/0922211 aEmerson, Caryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe First Hundred Years of Mikhail Bakhtin /cCaryl Emerson. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tINTRODUCTION. East Meets West in the Ex-USSR -- tPART ONE: EAXTHHOBEJJEHHE, EAXTHHHCTHKA, EAXTHHOJIOfHH: BAKHTIN STUDIES, BAKHTINISTICS, BAKHTINOLOGY -- tCHAPTER 1. The Russians Reclaim Bakhtin, 1975 to the Jubilee -- tCHAPTER 2. Retrospective: Domestic Reception during Bakhtin's Life -- tPART TWO: LITERATURE FADES, PHILOSOPHY MOVES TO THE FORE (REWORKING THREE PROBLEMATIC AREAS) -- tCHAPTER 3. Polyphony, Dialogism, Dostoevsky -- tCHAPTER 4. Carnival: Open-ended Bodies and Anachronistic Histories -- tCHAPTER 5. BHEHAOДИMOCTЬ: "Outsideness" as the Ethical Dimension of Art (Bakhtin and the Aesthetic Moment) -- tAFTERWORD. One Year Later: The Prospects for Bakhtin's HHOHayica [inonauka], or "Science in Some Other Way" -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong Western critics, Mikhail Bakhtin (1895-1975) needs no introduction. His name has been invoked in literary and cultural studies across the ideological spectrum, from old-fashioned humanist to structuralist to postmodernist. In this candid assessment of his place in Russian and Western thought, Caryl Emerson brings to light what might be unfamiliar to the non-Russian reader: Bakhtin's foundational ideas, forged in the early revolutionary years, yet hardly altered in his lifetime. With the collapse of the Soviet system, a truer sense of Bakhtin's contribution may now be judged in the context of its origins and its contemporary Russian "reclamation." A foremost Bakhtin authority, Caryl Emerson mines extensive Russian sources to explore Bakhtin's reception in Russia, from his earliest publication in 1929 until his death, and his posthumous rediscovery. After a reception-history of Bakhtin's published work, she examines the role of his ideas in the post-Stalinist revival of the Russian literary profession, concentrating on the most provocative rethinkings of three major concepts in his world: dialogue and polyphony; carnival; and "outsideness," a position Bakhtin considered essential to both ethics and aesthetics. Finally, she speculates on the future of Bakhtin's method, which was much more than a tool of criticism: it will "tell you how to teach, write, live, talk, think."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCriticismzRussia (Federation)xHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187037zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187037423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187037.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK